	  <title>Linear Equations – Quiz</title>
	  <caption>Linear Equations – Quiz</caption>
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>For each of the following expressions determine if it is a linear equation.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </question>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>4x - y + 11z = 14</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Yes!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘Yes!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! This is a linear equation in three variables.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>No!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘No!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Hmmm! Honest – I don't have a clue why you might think this equation is not linear, for it is!</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>x^2 + x + 1 = 0</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Yes!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘Yes!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry! – This equation is not linear because the variable <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> appears with its square <math>
                        <latex>x^2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>No!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘No!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! – This equation is not linear because the variable <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> appears with its square <math>
                        <latex>x^2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>2u - 3 + x = 3y - 2x</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Yes!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘Yes!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! – The given equation is equivalent to</para.body>
               </para>
					          <math.display>
						            <latex>2u -x - 3y = 3</latex>
					          </math.display>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>and this expression fits exactly the template of an inhomogeneous linear equation.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>No!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘No!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry! – This equation is linear. If you bring all expressions containing a variable to the left and the constant summand <math>
                        <latex>-3</latex>
                     </math> to the right, you will see that it fits exactly the template for a linear equation.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{2}\, x + \sin(\pi/2)\, y = 0</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Yes!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘Yes!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! – This is a homogeneous linear equation.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>No!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘No!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry! – This equation is linear. Perhaps the expression ‘<math>
                        <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                     </math>’ and ‘<math>
                        <latex>\sin(\pi/2)</latex>
                     </math>’ throw you off? – Remember: these are just complicated looking numbers; e.g. <math>
                        <latex>\sin(\pi/2) = 1</latex>
                     </math>. So the given equation fits exactly the template for a homogeneous linear equation in two variables.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
		    <part>
			      <question>
				        <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>e^{2x} - y = 3</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
			      </question>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Yes!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘Yes!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Sorry! – This equation is not linear because the variable <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> appears in the exponent of Euler’s number <math>
                        <latex>e</latex>
                     </math>. This is not allowed in a linear equation.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
			      <choice>
				        <answer>
               <para>
                  <para.body>No!</para.body>
               </para>
            </answer>
				        <info>
               <info.caption>Comment on ‘No!’</info.caption>
					
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Correct! – This equation is not linear because the variable <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> appears in the exponent of Euler’s number <math>
                        <latex>e</latex>
                     </math>. This is not allowed in a linear equation.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </info>
			      </choice>
		    </part>
	  </quiz>
	
	
</quiz.pack>
